Making the work place more desirable for adhds and other neurodivergent people to work in, making them want to stay on, rather than blaming them for leaving, I believe will be huge for any company that taps into it properly and fast. 

(Lots of big tech giants already do)

Who's replying when your service infrastructure goes down at midnight? Adhds. Who's highly skilled in niche areas of new development? Adhds. Who innovates all your processes that haven't changed in 30 years just cause they hated using them? Adhds.

Its always 'adhd is a disability we need to cater the work place to in order to be more inclusive' and never 'adhd is a neurodivergence where your brain works differently to this one size fits all version of success built on the industrial revolution over 100 years ago'

It's always 'adhds can't work consistently' and never 'maintaining consistency is less productive for adhds as will have to expend energy on masking that they work more effectively when they are given room to work how, what and when they want'
It's always 'adhds aren't loyal' and never the consideration that we're going to be hyper loyal to any environment that allows us to thrive because they are so immensely rare and precise to our needs

It's always 'your CV looks bad cause youre a job hopper' never 'wow you've learned so many new skills at your old job and convinced a complete stranger that you're worth more than you're currently paid so many times in the past 3 years' huh?

It's always 'adhds have lots of different, short stint jobs cause they give up/are bored' and never 'adhds are highly adaptable and hireable quick learners thus regularly successfully interview for new opportunities they are interested in' huh?
